                <head>160. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>During the morning of May 15, <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>
                    paid a visit to <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName> at the Elysée
                    Palace. Accompanied by <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>,
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_VSA1">Vinogradov</persName>, and Minister of
                    Defense <persName corresp="#p_MMRY1">Malinovsky</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> launched into an attack on the
                    United States, and handed <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">De Gaulle</persName> a
                    declaration that stated that unless President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> publicly apologized for the U–2 incident, announced
                    that those responsible would be punished, and stated that no U.S. spy planes
                    would overfly the Soviet Union again, he would take no part in the summit
                    conference.</p>
                <p>For two accounts of this meeting, see <persName corresp="#p_dGC1">De
                        Gaulle</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Mémoires</hi>, pages 260–261, and <hi
                        rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> Remembers: The Last
                        Testament</hi>, pages 452–453. A copy of the declaration was transmitted in
                        <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 14 from Paris, May 16. (Department
                    of State, Conference Files: Lot 64 D 559, <gloss target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss>
                    1666)</p>
            </div>
